There could be some relief from power cuts next month as the Eskom CEO says 3,000 megawatts will be added to the grid from neighbouring countries. #dstv403 JOHANNESBURG - A total of 3,000 megawatts of electricity will be added to the grid by March. That is according to outgoing Eskom CEO, Andre de Ruyter. READ: SA’s electricity crisis | State of disaster not welcomed The extra capacity is equal to three stages of rolling blackouts. "We have been advocating for at least three years, we have secured additional imports from our neighbours," said De Ruyter. READ: De Ruyter: Eskom paying for past sins "There are delays. However, the matters are enjoying the attention of the crisis committee." Briefing Parliament, De Ruyter also said non-paying municipalities are costing the utility over R57-billion.